    <h1>Cor&#xAD;beri quits kart&#xAD;ing in dis&#xAD;grace af&#xAD;ter clash</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201007/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-07"><time>2020-10-07</time></a>
        - <span>SPORT</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>LONDON • An Ital­ian who threw part of his go-kart at a ri­val dur­ing a world cham­pi­onship fi­nal, prompt­ing 2009 For­mula One cham­pion Jenson But­ton to call for a life ban, apol­o­gised on Mon­day and said he was leav­ing the sport.</p>
    <p>Cov­er­age of the KZ fi­nal on YouTube showed 23-year-old Luca Cor­beri crash­ing out and wait­ing by the side of the track for ri­val Paolo Ip­polito be­fore hurl­ing his kart’s bumper at him.</p>
    <p>The Gazzetta dello Sport web­site said Cor­beri had posted an apol­ogy on Face­book, quot­ing him as say­ing: “I have de­cided not to take part in any other mo­tor­sport com­pe­ti­tion for the rest of my life.” The gov­ern­ing FIA said it had launched an im­me­di­ate in­ves­ti­ga­tion.</p>


